## 9. Architectural Judgment Question

### Q18. Default-in-code + deployment override vs. deployment-only configuration

**Answer:**

| Criteria | Default-in-code + Override | Deployment-only |
|---|---|---|
| **Maintainability** | High — defaults live with the code that uses them; easy to find and update | Low — config and code are decoupled; easy to lose sync |
| **Scalability** | Scales well — new services boot with zero config; only overrides needed | Scales poorly — every new environment needs full config |
| **Reliability** | High — system always has a working baseline | Lower — missing key = failure |
| **Developer experience** | Excellent — clone, run, it works | Poor — clone, hunt for config template, fill in values, then run |
| **Security** | Requires discipline to choose safe defaults | Forces explicit decisions (can be an advantage) |

**Verdict:**

**Default-in-code + deployment override** is the superior pattern for most systems. It provides resilience, developer ergonomics, and operational simplicity. The exception is security-critical or infrastructure config where no safe default exists — those should be mandatory.

**Use Case — Monolith to microservices migration:**
A monolith has 200 config keys. Moving to deployment-only config means every microservice needs a massive config file. With defaults-in-code, each service defines its own defaults and only overrides what differs per environment. Ops manages 10 overrides per service instead of 200 mandatory keys.

